\subsection{Retrieval Benefits Syntactic Contrasts}
We begin by investigating the general effectiveness of retrieval augmentation on syntactic contrasts. Table~\ref{tab:general_effects} shows that $k$NN augmentation improves performance across all three syntactic phenomena and both pretraining scales, as well as replicating previously reported perplexity improvements \citep{khandelwal2020knnlm}. Relative clauses benefit the most from retrieval augmentation across both model scales, while gains for wh-questions and subject-verb agreement are more modest. This pattern holds consistently regardless of pretraining scale, though perplexity reductions are larger for the large-scale model. The disproportionate benefit for relative clauses suggests that retrieval is most helpful where parametric representations are weakest, which motivates us to analyze the performance gains stratified by frequency.


\subsection{Frequency Gap is Narrowed but not Fully Closed}
\label{sec:frequency_effects}

Next, we examine whether retrieval helps close the lexical frequency gap. Table~\ref{tab:frequency_effects} confirms the existence of frequency gaps in both baseline models across three syntactic phenomena, with performance on low-frequency items consistently lower than on high-frequency items. With retrieval augmentation, low-frequency items benefit more than high-frequency ones across all phenomena and both model scales. This pattern is the most pronounced for relative clauses. %%In contrast, high-frequency items show minimal or no improvement with retrieval. 
Nevertheless, this compensation is not sufficient to eliminate the frequency gap: low-frequency items still systematically yield lower accuracy than high-frequency items across all tested phenomena and both model scales, even after retrieval augmentation. %The frequency-based performance gap thus persists, though to a reduced extent, after retrieval intervention.



\section{Analysis}
\subsection{Importance of Structural vs. Semantic Information}
\label{sec:multidimensional_binding}


We proceed to investigate which aspects of the retrieved information drive the observed benefits by examining (1) the effect of semantics-only retrieval, and (2) the effect of retrieving structurally similar instances.


\noindent \textbf{Semantics-only retrieval is mostly ineffective.} 
Figure~\ref{fig:vector} shows that semantics-only retrieval (both summed uncontextualized embeddings and averaged contextualized embeddings: see Section~\ref{subsec:datastores}) performs at or substantially \textit{below} baseline across most conditions. This shows that semantically similar but structurally irrelevant examples may actively mislead syntactic judgments. One partial exception is GPT2-Averaged, where phrase- and sequence-level retrieval does lead to gains over the baseline for low-frequency items for RCs, although performance on high-frequency items degrades by a large margin. There are two possible, non-mutually exclusive interpretations for this: (1) semantic information does sometimes yield benefits, as discussed in the next paragraph; or (2) that averaging of contextualized embeddings does not totally remove structural information.




