\noindent \textbf{Structural information is critical; semantic information benefit is comparatively minor.} 

Figure~\ref{fig:datastore} examines retrieval benefits in two aspects: whether the datastore contains structurally matching examples (\emph{with} vs.\ \emph{without}), and whether retrieval ranks them by embedding similarity or at random (\emph{+r}).\footnote{See Appendix~\ref{app:struc_simi} for our structural-similarity metric and its validation.} 


Across all phenomena and both scales, the \emph{w/+r} 
bars consistently exceed the \emph{w/o+r} bars, with the largest gaps on relative clauses in low-frequency items. Embedding-similarity ranking yields smaller additional gains, more pronounced for low-frequency items. These results indicate that effective episodic retrieval for syntactic contrasts requires representations that encode \emph{structural} information; semantic information plays a comparatively minor role.

% ------------------- END OF version showing on COLM submission
%Next, we investigate whether structural information is critical for retrieval benefits by examining the actual retrieved sequences and dividing the results by examples for which items with high structural similarity\footnote{See Supplementary Materials for our metric of structural similarity and its validation.} were retrieved and examples for which they were not. In general, when the retrieved sequences contain structurally overlapping examples (columns ``with'', Table~\ref{tab:structural_overlap_with_struc}), the benefits are greater compared to when the retrieved sentences do not contain such examples (columns ``without'', Table~\ref{tab:structural_overlap_with_struc}), again highlighting the importance of structural information. Still, even in cases where structurally overlapping examples are not retrieved, some minor gains are observed, suggesting that some benefits do derive from semantic information. 




