    \caption{Performance across retrieval granularities (token, phrase, sequence) in child-realistic (top row) and large-scale (bottom row) models ($k=1$, $\tau=3$). Blue bars indicate high-frequency items and orange bars low-frequency items. Optimal granularity varies by phenomenon and frequency: sequence-level retrieval generally performs best for low-frequency items in wh-questions and relative clauses, while patterns for subject-verb agreement vary by model scale.}

    \label{fig:granularity}
\end{figure*}


We next analyze whether and how retrieval effectiveness is modulated by three configuration parameters: retrieval granularity (token, phrase, or sequence), number of neighbors ($k$), and context window size ($\tau$). 
% A general observation is that, across these three configuration parameters, no single setting yields optimal performance across all syntactic phenomena and frequency strata. 


\noindent \textbf{Effects of retrieval granularity.}
Figure~\ref{fig:granularity} shows that optimal granularity varies by syntactic phenomenon and frequency strata. Sequence-level retrieval yields the best performance for low-frequency Wh and RC across both models, suggesting that phenomena with longer-range dependencies benefit from retrieval of longer contexts. For low-frequency SV, phrase-level retrieval performs best in the child-realistic model, while sequence-level dominates in the large-scale model, demonstrating an interaction with model capacity.



\noindent \textbf{Effects of context window size.} 
Figure~\ref{fig:context_effects} shows that larger context windows ($\tau=10$) generally yield stronger performance for structurally complex phenomena such as relative clauses. Subject-verb agreement (SV) remains comparatively stable across window sizes, while Wh-questions show intermediate sensitivity to context size. 
These patterns suggest that longer-range dependencies require broader context to be resolved, whereas simpler dependencies are less sensitive to window size.


