\subsection{Evaluation set construction}
\label{app:subset_selection}

To ensure focused evaluation on syntactic phenomena relevant to our research questions, we selected subsets corresponding to our target phenomena from three evaluation benchmarks: BLiMP \citep{warstadt2020blimp}, Zorro \citep{huebner2021babyberta}, and BIG-Bench \citep{srivastava2023beyond} as discussed below.

\subsubsection{Source benchmarks}

\textbf{BLiMP.} The Benchmark of Linguistic Minimal Pairs for English \citep{warstadt2020blimp} consists of 67 sub-datasets, each containing 1,000 minimal pairs (67,000 pairs total) isolating specific contrasts in syntax, morphology, or semantics. The data is automatically generated according to linguist-crafted grammar templates, with 96.4\% aggregate human agreement with the labels. 

\textbf{Zorro.} Zorro \citep{huebner2021babyberta} is a grammar test suite designed for models trained on child-directed language, consisting of 13 phenomena with multiple paradigms. Zorro contains approximately 1,000 minimal pairs per paradigm, with lexical items selected to be compatible with the smaller vocabularies of child-trained models. 

\textbf{BIG-Bench.} The Beyond the Imitation Game Benchmark \citep{srivastava2023beyond} includes numerous linguistic evaluation tasks. We selected relevant subject-verb agreement and syntactic construction tasks from this benchmark.

\subsubsection{Instance selection procedure}

For each evaluation instance in the original datasets, we selected instances containing one or more of the following syntactic structures using spaCy \citep{honnibal2020spacy}.

\textbf{Subject-Verb detection.} We applied spaCy's dependency parser to identify subject-verb relationships. Instances were flagged if they contained \texttt{nsubj} (nominal subject) or \texttt{nsubjpass} (passive nominal subject) dependencies linking a noun phrase to a finite verb.

\textbf{Wh-Sentence detection.} We used part-of-speech (POS) tagging to identify wh-words (POS tags: \texttt{WDT}, \texttt{WP}, \texttt{WP\$}, \texttt{WRB}) at clause boundaries, following standard Penn Treebank conventions \citep{marcus1993building}. Instances containing interrogative or relative wh-elements were marked for inclusion.

\textbf{Relative Clause detection.} We combined POS tagging with dependency parsing to identify relative clause structures. Specifically, we detected: (1) Relative pronouns (\texttt{WDT}, \texttt{WP}) or relativizers (\emph{that}, \emph{which}, \emph{who}); (2) Clausal complements with \texttt{relcl} (relative clause modifier) dependency relations; and (3) Appropriate structural embedding within a noun phrase.


\subsection{Structural similarity analysis}
\label{app:struc_simi}

Structural similarity (used in the analysis in Section~\ref{sec:multidimensional_binding}) is defined as dependency arc overlap between retrieved and target sentences. We used spaCy's dependency parser \citep{honnibal2020spacy}, measuring the proportion of matching subject, object, and modifier relations. Table~\ref{tab:dependency_similarity} shows that full contextualized retrieval (GPT2-Context) maintains substantially higher structural similarity than uncontextualized embeddings (FastText, GloVe). Averaged contextualized embeddings (GPT2-Averaged) show intermediate structural preservation, consistent with our interpretation in Section~\ref{sec:multidimensional_binding} that averaging reduces but does not fully eliminate structural information. These structural similarity scores directly correspond to the performance patterns in Table~\ref{tab:datastore_comparison}: high structural similarity correlates with retrieval benefits, while low structural similarity leads to performance at or below baseline.

