\subsection{Full Retrieval Configuration Results}
\label{app:retrieval_config}

This section provides complete results across all retrieval configuration combinations discussed in Section~\ref{sec:frequency_effects}. We vary three parameters independently: number of retrieved neighbors ($k \in \{1, 16, 1024\}$), context window size ($\tau \in \{1, 3, 10\}$), and retrieval granularity (token, phrase, sequence). Table~\ref{tab:syntactic_granularity_with_k} reports accuracy for representative configurations ($\tau \in \{3, 10\}$, $k=16$) across both model scales, andFigures~\ref{fig:app_context_gpt2xl_k1}--\ref{fig:app_neighbor_child_tau3}
provide complete visualizations across all parameter combinations.

\noindent \textbf{Effects of context window size.}
% compared with the baseline, any number of context window 

Figures~\ref{fig:app_context_gpt2xl_k1}--\ref{fig:app_context_child_k1024}
show the effect of context window size ($\tau \in \{1, 3, 10\}$) across granularities, phenomena, frequency bands, and both model scales. 
The most pronounced pattern is that \textbf{sequence-level retrieval benefits most from larger context windows in structurally complex phenomena like relative clauses}. For example, in GPT-2 XL at $k=1$, sequence-level retrieval for low-frequency relative clauses shows clear improvements as $\tau$ increases from 1 to 10, while the corresponding high-frequency items remain largely stable (Figures~\ref{fig:app_context_gpt2xl_k1}f and~\ref{fig:app_context_gpt2xl_k1}i). By contrast, there is no consistent pattern on token- and phrase- level across syntactic phenomena. 

%----old version------
% For low-frequency items, larger context windows ($\tau=10$) generally yield stronger performance, with the benefit most pronounced for sequence-level retrieval and structurally complex phenomena (Wh and RCs). For example, in GPT-2 XL at $k=1$, sequence-level retrieval for low-frequency RCs improves, while high-frequency RCs show minimal change.
% Token-level retrieval consistently benefits from larger context windows across all phenomena, as wider context provides richer representational signal for nearest-neighbor matching. Phrase- and sequence-level retrieval are comparatively more stable across window sizes, suggesting that longer retrieval units already capture sufficient structural context at smaller $\tau$. For subject-verb agreement, which involves shorter-range dependencies, context window size has the least impact, particularly for high-frequency items where parametric representations are already strong.



% Comparing $k=1$ (Figures~\ref{fig:app_context_gpt2xl_k1} and
% \ref{fig:app_context_child_k1}) against $k=1024$
% (Figures~\ref{fig:app_context_gpt2xl_k1024} and
% \ref{fig:app_context_child_k1024}) reveals an important interaction: at large $k$, the benefit of increasing context window size is substantially reduced or reversed for low-frequency items, particularly for RCs and Wh-questions. This suggests that larger context windows help select better individual neighbors, but this advantage is overwhelmed by noise when too many neighbors are retrieved. The child-realistic model (Figures~\ref{fig:app_context_child_k1} and \ref{fig:app_context_child_k1024}) shows qualitatively similar patterns to GPT-2 XL but with smaller absolute gains throughout, consistent with its weaker parametric base.

\noindent \textbf{Effects of number of retrieved neighbors.}
Figures~\ref{fig:app_neighbor_gpt2xl_tau1}--\ref{fig:app_neighbor_child_tau3}
show the effect of varying $k \in \{1, 16, 1024\}$ across granularities, phenomena, and frequency bands. The non-monotonic pattern reported in the main text is robust across all configurations: moving from $k=1$ to $k=16$ consistently improves performance for low-frequency items, while increasing further to $k=1024$ leads to degradation. This pattern is most pronounced for sequence-level retrieval and structurally complex phenomena: for both GPT-2 XL and the child-realistic model, at $\tau=3$, sequence-level retrieval for low-frequency RCs peaks at $k=16$ compared to $k=1$ and $k=1024$. The degradation at $k=1024$ is most pronounced for sequence-level retrieval and for structurally complex phenomena.
For simpler phenomena such as subject-verb agreement, and for high-frequency items more generally, both the gains at $k=16$ and the degradation at $k=1024$ are more modest.

Comparing $\tau=1$(Figures~\ref{fig:app_neighbor_gpt2xl_tau1} and
\ref{fig:app_neighbor_child_tau1}) against $\tau=3$
(Figures~\ref{fig:app_neighbor_gpt2xl_tau3} and
\ref{fig:app_neighbor_child_tau3}) shows that larger context windows amplify 
the benefit of moderate aggregation: at $\tau=3$, moderate aggregation at $k=16$ provides stronger gains for sequence-level low-frequency items compared to $\tau=1$. The degradation at $k=1024$, however, remains close at $\tau=3$ as at $\tau=1$, confirming that over-retrieval noise cannot be mitigated by wider context alone. The child-realistic model exhibits the same non-monotonic pattern as GPT-2 XL but with a more pronounced drop at $k=1024$, particularly for low-frequency relative clauses and Wh-questions

% consistent with its representations being more susceptible to retrieval noise.
